<DOC><DOCNO> AP880503-0205 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2111EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-03 0409</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</SECOND><BYLINE>Showers and Thunderstorms Cover Central States^By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Showers and thunderstorms covered much of the central UnitedStates Tuesday and pelted Arkansas and Missouri with hail, afterareas of Kansas and Nebraska soaked up more than 5 inches of rain.   Sunny skies prevailed over the northern Midwest states, andtemperatures soared into the upper 70s in central and northernMinnesota.   The heaviest thunderstorms hit northern Arkansas, Missouri andeastern Kansas.   In northeast Arkansas, walnut-size hail was reported nearPocahontas and one-inch hail fell in Lawrence County. Marble-sizehail was reported in several parts of central Missouri.   Showers and thunderstorms also stretched from western Tennesseeto the Missouri Valley into eastern South Dakota. There were also afew showers over eastern Pennsylvania and eastern Maryland and overthe central Gulf Coast.   Rain tapered off during the morning over Kansas and Nebraska. Inthe 24 hours ending at 8 a.m. EDT Tuesday, McDonald, Kan. reported5} inches of rain and 4 inches were recorded during the same periodover parts of central Nebraska.   Skies were sunny over Michigan and Wisconsin and temperaturesclimbed well into the 70s in Minnesota. International Falls, Minn.,on the Canadian border, registered a balmy 77 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT.   Skies were cloudy and temperatures stayed in the 40s and 50sover the northern and central Plains. Temperatures in New Englandalso stayed cool in the 50s.   Showers continued along coastal sections of the PacificNorthwest with some snow at the higher elevations. A snow advisorywas in effect for the Oregon Cascades.   Sunny skies and warm temperatures prevailed from central Texasto southern California.   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 37 degrees atYellowstone, Wyo., to 89 degrees at Cotulla, Texas, and Chase NavalAir Station, Beeville, Texas.   The low for the nation Tuesday morning was 7 degrees atGunnison, Colo.   Showers and thunderstorms were forecast Wednesday to extend fromthe Middle Atlantic states to the Carolinas and into the Tennesseeand Ohio Valleys. Showers and thunderstorms also were predicted tostretch from the northern Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies andinto northern Nevada.   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 50s in Washington,Oregon, western Idaho, northwest Nevada and northern California.Highs were forecast in the 80s in Florida, the Gulf Coast and mostof Texas, and into the 90s in the desert southwest. Highs elsewherewere forecast to be in the 60s or 70s.</TEXT></DOC>